\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. P. dilatatum} Poiret in Lam.,{\i  Encycl. Méth. Bot.}{\b  5}: 35 (1804) ({\i Digitaria dilatata} (Poiret) Coste). Caespitose perennial; stems 40-180 cm, ascending. Inflorescence of (2-)3-5(-11) racemes on a common axis 2-20 cm; raceme 4-11 cm, with narrowly winged rhachis. Spikelets 2·8-3·8 mm, ovate, yellowish-green; upper glume sparsely hairy on the surface, more densely villous near the margin; lower lemma similar but glabrous. 2n = 50.{\i  Damp, shady places and waste ground. S.W. Europe and Italy}. [Az Ga Hs It Lu.] ({\i Brazil to Argentina.})
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. P. urvillei} Steudel,{\i  Syn. Pl. Glum.}{\b  1}: 24 (1853). Like {\b 1} but stems 75-250 cm, erect; inflorescence of (6-)12-18(-25) racemes on a common axis 10-40 cm; raceme 7-14 cm; spikelets 2-3 mm. 2n = 20.{\i  Rice-fields and other wet places. Naturalized in W.C. Portugal and perhaps elsewhere in S. Europe.} [Lu.] ({\i Brazil to Argentina}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. P. paspalodes} (Michx) Scribner, {\i Ment. Torrey Bot. Club }{\b 5}: 29 (1894). Creeping stoloniferous perennial; stems 6-50 cm. Sheaths ciliate on margin. Inflorescence of 2(-4) racemes; racemes 1·5-7 cm, with a narrow, flattened rhachis. Spikelets 2·5-3·5 mm, ovate, plano-convex, relatively plump, pale green; lower glume often present as a small scale; upper glume appressed-puberulent, herbaceous, with distinct mid-vein; lower lemma similar but glabrous. 2n = 60. {\i Marshy places, mainly near the coast. S. Europe}. [Al Az Bu Ga Gr Hs It Lu Rs (K) Tu.] ({\i Tropics}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 4. P. vaginatum} Swartz,{\i  Nov. Gen. Sp. Pl.} 21 (1788) ({\i Digitaria vaginata} (Swartz) Philippe). Like {\b 3} but sheaths glabrous at apex, though ligule ciliate on back; spikelets ovate-elliptical, flattened; lower glume nearly always absent; upper glume glabrous, thinly papery, the mid-vein obscure. 2n = 20. {\i Maritime sands and ricefields. S.W. Europe, Sicilia.} [Ga Hs Lu Si.] ({\i Tropics}.)
\par

